# Project Structure Rules

- This repo is a multilingual `Next.js 16` app that mixes content pages, blog layouts, and interactive tools. Structure changes should preserve that split instead of flattening everything into shared global code.
- Preferred ownership:
  - `app/`: routes, metadata, route shells, API handlers
  - `components/`: shared UI primitives and reusable islands
  - `layouts/`: blog/content-specific page wrappers
  - `data/`: static metadata, navigation, author/content config
  - `utils/`: framework-agnostic helpers
  - route-local `components/` and hooks: feature-specific behavior
- Keep reusable abstractions honest. Do not move feature-specific logic into shared directories unless at least two real surfaces benefit.
- Preserve deployment-critical files and flow:
  - `contentlayer.config.ts` defines generated content contracts
  - `package.json` build must keep explicit `contentlayer` generation before production build
  - `next.config.js` holds image, plugin, and bundler compatibility choices
  - `proxy.ts` owns locale-aware request rewriting
- Prefer colocating complex tool UI with its route. Blog/content primitives can stay more centralized under `components/` and `layouts/`.
- Static assets belong in `public/` when served directly, or route/app asset directories when imported. Choose the path that best preserves optimization and bundle clarity.
- When reorganizing files, consider mobile/desktop implications too: route-local styles and media decisions often depend on the actual viewport behavior of that feature.
- Any structure or config refactor should be checked against three failure modes common in this repo:
  - content generation/build breakage
  - hydration/runtime mismatch from client-only code
  - CLS/image regressions on both phone and desktop layouts
